Algernon

Target IP: 192.168.197.65

Algernon sure is a clever one.

Reconnaissance


There are five TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.


Performing an aggressive nmap scan returns the result above. The FTP and HTTP applications are interesting to me.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

The FTP application allows anonymous login. There are four directories: ImapRetrieval, Logs, PopRetrieval, and Spool. Maybe these directories contain useful information?


There is one log file called 2020.05.12-administrative.log. I downloaded this file on my machine.


The content of this 2020.05.12-administrative.log log file is shown above. This was the odd one out file from the directory. There is a Webmail application on the target machine. I downloaded more log files on my machine and it looks like there is ClamAV installed. But I did not find anything more interesting here.


After doing more nmap scan, I found port 9998 is open. And browsing to this port displays the webpage above. A blank webpage is displayed. Is this the Webmail application I found from previous enumeration?


Using the view-source tag, I viewed the source code of this application. The target machine is running Smarter Mail 100.0.6919.

Exploitation & Flag


I found the working exploit above on Github for this application. I downloaded this exploit on my machine.


Then I changed the lines highlighted in yellow in the picture above. Then I started a listener on port 8443.


After making the changes, I launched the exploit. Then I obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as nt authority\system. In the picture above, the top terminal is where I obtained the reverse shell and the bottom terminal is where I deploy the exploit. I do not need to perform privilege escalation on this machine.


The flag is shown above after gaining system access on the system.
